The retrieved evidence consistently states that acromegaly results from excessive growth hormone secretion **after** the fusion of the long bone epiphyses. This contrasts with gigantism, which occurs before epiphyseal closure and allows for continued longitudinal bone growth. Thus, acromegaly does not contribute to height increase through linear growth but instead promotes pathological soft tissue and bone thickening in adults—supporting option B. All cited references emphasize this distinction, confirming the correct answer. \boxed{B}

